{"award_age":55.0,"bio_image":"full\/ae70db80cbff4995f54f29aa791c83f12b78edc8.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1903-10-22T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1989-06-09T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/2\/24\/George_Wells_Beadle.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Wells_Beadle","mini_bio":"<p><b>George Wells Beadle<\/b> (October 22, 1903 \u2013 June 9, 1989) was an American <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Scientist\" title=\"Scientist\">scientist<\/a> in the field of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetics\" title=\"Genetics\">genetics<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_laureate\" title=\"Nobel laureate\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel laureate<\/a> who with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edward_Lawrie_Tatum\" title=\"Edward Lawrie Tatum\">Edward Lawrie Tatum<\/a> discovered the role of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gene\" title=\"Gene\">genes<\/a> in regulating biochemical events within cells in 1958.<sup id=\"cite_ref-nas_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Wells_Beadle#cite_note-nas-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Wells_Beadle#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Beadle and Tatum's key experiments involved exposing the bread <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mold\" title=\"Mold\">mold<\/a> <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Neurospora_crassa\" title=\"Neurospora crassa\">Neurospora crassa<\/a><\/i> to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/X-ray\" title=\"X-ray\">x-rays<\/a>, causing <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mutation\" title=\"Mutation\">mutations<\/a>. In a series of experiments, they showed that these mutations caused changes in specific <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Enzyme\" title=\"Enzyme\">enzymes<\/a> involved in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Metabolic_pathway\" title=\"Metabolic pathway\">metabolic pathways<\/a>. These experiments led them to propose a direct link between genes and enzymatic reactions, known as the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/One_gene-one_enzyme_hypothesis\" title=\"One gene-one enzyme hypothesis\">One gene-one enzyme hypothesis<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-onegeneonenz_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Wells_Beadle#cite_note-onegeneonenz-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"George Beadle","place_of_birth":"Wahoo, Nebraska ,  USA","place_of_death":"Chicago, Illinois ,  USA","text":"George Beadle , Physiology or Medicine, 1958","year":1958.0}